  abstract-en: (
    content: [
      Three-dimensional reconstruction is important in computer vision, graphics, and robotic perception, with applications in digital twins, virtual reality, industrial inspection, cultural heritage preservation, and automated scanning. Neural rendering representations such as Neural Radiance Fields and 3D Gaussian Splatting have improved novel view synthesis, but reconstruction quality still depends strongly on input-view coverage. Under sparse-view conditions, occluded regions, back-side surfaces, complex materials, and distant backgrounds may suffer from blur, ghosting, structural discontinuities, and color drift. Therefore, selecting the most informative next view from the current reconstruction state is a key problem in active 3D reconstruction.

      This thesis studies an active 3D reconstruction method based on data-driven uncertainty. The system uses 3D Gaussian representation as the reconstruction backbone and organizes active reconstruction as a closed loop of initial sampling, current reconstruction, candidate-view rendering, uncertainty estimation, and view update. At each selection round, the system renders color and depth maps for candidate views, predicts unreliable regions, and adds the candidate view with the highest overall uncertainty score into the training set. Different from methods based only on geometric coverage, Fisher information, or image quality, the proposed method jointly exploits appearance artifacts and geometric instability, making the candidate score more related to the actual reconstruction error.

      Methodologically, this thesis designs a joint color-depth uncertainty estimation model. The color branch predicts appearance uncertainty caused by blur, color drift, ghosting, and specular artifacts, while the depth branch captures geometric uncertainty caused by discontinuities, unstable occlusion boundaries, and incorrect spatial ordering. A depth-aware fusion strategy and a depth-uncertainty reweighting strategy combine color uncertainty, depth values, and depth reliability into a unified candidate-view score. Pixel-level labels are generated automatically from structural similarity errors between held-out rendered images and ground-truth images.

      Experiments on object-level reconstruction, complex material objects, scene-level reconstruction, and real robotic scanning show that the proposed method outperforms random selection, image-quality-based methods, and information-theoretic methods in average and worst-view quality. Ablation studies demonstrate the contributions of depth-aware fusion and depth-uncertainty reweighting. Robotic scanning experiments further show that data-driven uncertainty scoring can be transferred to a robotic acquisition pipeline for next-view and scanning-path decisions.
    ],
    keywords: ("active 3D reconstruction", "data-driven uncertainty", "3D Gaussian Splatting", "next-best-view", "robotic scanning"),
  ),
